<HEAD>South African Granite Scrapped For Bus Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's transit and sewage authority is giving up $ 480,000 of granite it bought for a downtown bus tunnel because the stone came from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the agency announced. `` It would violate the spirit of our policy and would be an affront to the community'' to use the granite, executive <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Thursday. The granite _ enough to cover 24,000 square feet _ is sitting in supply yards in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, where it was cut. `` We're going to have to eat the cost,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalberer </PERSON>, superintendent of the $ 430 million tunnel project. <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> hopes to sell the granite for scrap to recoup some of the cost, he added. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Royer </PERSON> agreed with the decision. `` This could be a serious affront and embarrassment for lots of people,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> banned the purchase of South African goods because of that country's policy of racial segregation, or apartheid, after a county councilman and city councilman protested the use of South African steel in tunnel work in 1987.
