<HEAD>First Man To Register Under New Law Now Too Old To Be Drafted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first man since the Vietnam War to get through eight years of draft eligibility without being called to arms said something was missing from his 26th birthday celebration. `` I'm proud within myself about it. I wish I had an award or something though. That would have been nice. Maybe a plaque to hang on the wall,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, the first 18-year-old to sign up and be processed by the Selective Service System after draft registration was revived in 1981, turned 26 on Friday. That made him too old to be called up even if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president reactivate the draft, according to <ORGANIZATION> Selective </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I did n't have to go active and I'm glad about that,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. `` But if it was God's will I would have gone. It's a blessing to be a soldier for this country.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said he had no idea he was the first man in the country to register when he did so. He said he just followed the law and signed up. `` I was n't worried about being drafted when I was 18. I do n't think I even thought about it, but if it had happened it would have just happened When I turned 21 I got more worried about it,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. The draft was stopped in 1973 after the end of the Vietnam War, but registration was revived on Jan. 5, 1981. Federal law requires every man to register with <ORGANIZATION> Selective </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> within 30 days of his 18th birthday.
</TEXT>
