<HEAD>``Take-It-Easy'' Program Reduces Premature Births, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A program that included paid work leaves and avoiding physical exertion cut the premature birth rate at a French hospital by a third, but its cost-effectiveness is debatable, researchers say. Participants could take longer leaves than the six-week paid leave available to <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> women before their due date, said researcher <PERSON> Emile </PERSON> <PERSON> Papiernik </PERSON>. For example, a woman whose job involved a lot of standing might begin the leave 10 weeks before the due date, said <PERSON> Papiernik </PERSON>, chairman of the obstetrics and gynecology department at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. The program also included teaching women to avoid physically taxing situations at home like moving a household, and to follow such steps as sitting rather than standing when washing clothes, <PERSON> Papiernik </PERSON> said Friday in an interview. It also stressed close relationships with caregivers, he said. The overall goal was to reduce physical exertion that triggers the uterus to contract during pregnancy. A study of more than 16,000 deliveries at the hospital found that while premature deliveries stood at 5.4 percent of live births for 1971-74, they decreased to 3.6 percent for 1979-82. The study could not demonstrate statistically that work leaves themselves made a difference, but they probably helped, <PERSON> Papiernik </PERSON> wrote in a book about the research. But an American expert said the French approach would incur `` inappropriate and unnecessary costs'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because most participants would have had full-term pregnancies anyway. Most women at risk for premature births carry their fetuses to term, and physicians can not predict with great accuracy who will deliver prematurely, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> also said many women may not want to pass up economic and psychological benefits of working. He and <PERSON> Papiernik </PERSON> spoke at a seminar sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> March </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dimes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Birth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Some 350,000 American babies every year are born more than three weeks before the end of the normal 40-week term, the foundation says. They account for 70 percent of infant deaths, and are at risk for such problems as cerebral palsy, seizure disorders, mental retardation, and impairments of vision and hearing.
