<FIRST>r a PM-POWCallBack     01-07 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-POW Call Back,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Mary Anne' Calls Back, Makes Connection with POW Her Family Rescued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the 44 years since he survived a massacre of Americans at a Japanese prisoner of war camp in World War II, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> had often wondered what happened to his Filipino rescuers. A balky telephone answering machine almost cost him a chance to find out. But thanks to the persistence of a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> nurse named <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ancheta </PERSON>, <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> finally has been able to track down the guerrilla band that saved him. Forty-four years ago, Mrs. <PERSON> Ancheta </PERSON> was <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Major </PERSON>, a 7-year-old whose father ran a guerrilla camp in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>; <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> was a young Marine who was brought into the camp with malaria. `` He was shaking like a leaf, he had the chills,'' she said Friday. `` I remember him, although I did n't remember his name.'' Last month, she noticed an article about a reunion of American prisoners of war in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, saw <PERSON> McDole </PERSON>'s name and called his home on New Year's Eve. But the tape on his answering machine ran out and he did n't get her last name or phone number. Publicity about his request to have `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>'' call again resulted in a story in a <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> newspaper Wednesday. Mrs. <PERSON> Ancheta </PERSON> saw it and called <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> on Thursday. `` I saw it at 11 at night and it was too late to call. I could n't sleep and I called the next morning,'' she said `` I felt like I have known him all that while. It's overwhelming. I'm so glad to know he's alive and well after all that ordeal.'' For <PERSON> McDole </PERSON>, the conversation recalled December 1944, when he and about 150 other Americans were held by the Japanese in <LOCATION> Palawan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>. He had been there 33 months when <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> forces staged an invasion nearby. `` They made a feint to come toward us but turned away,'' <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> recalled. `` That's when the Japanese decided to annihilate the group of prisoners. They had us down in trenches, and they threw in gasoline and torches. The ones who climbed over the edge were machine gunned.'' <PERSON> McDole </PERSON>'s trench was the one nearest to a 60-foot cliff overlooking a bay. `` We had started digging through anyway, and we knocked the side of ours out and went over the cliff. I think 20, 25 of us made it to the beach, but some of them panicked and they were gunned down. `` I got pinned down and hid under a pile of garbage. I stayed there all night and part of the next day. I thought I was the only man of the 150 to be alive. You do a lot of praying and crying, and I knew that if I did n't make it, nobody would know what happened. They -LRB- the Japanese -RRB- would probably blame it on our own planes.'' Of the 150 prisoners, 11 escaped and six were brought to the guerrilla camp run by Maziro Major, now 88 and retired in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> after a career in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. `` It turns out he was educated in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, which is where he met his wife,'' <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> said. `` They were wonderful to us. They saved our lives.'' The rebels protected and healed the Americans for a month, when they were picked up by a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sea plane. The two groups never made contact again. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> eventually became a nurse in the office of her husband, Dr. <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> <PERSON> Ancheta </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Algoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, while <PERSON> McDole </PERSON>, 67, is now chief of the patrol division of the <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's office. <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> said he, too, was overwhelmed by the call. `` It's brought back some of the concerns of what happened to the family. I've thought about them all a lot Then all of a sudden, boom, you get a call and I find out the captain is still alive and this is his daughter. I'm going to get a letter off to the captain today. I feel real good.'' `` All these years, I had been hoping to meet one of those men,'' she said. She and <PERSON> McDole </PERSON> said they both hope to attend a reunion next December.
