<FIRST>r i PM-Hirohito-Empress     01-07 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Empress,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once Familiar, Empress Now Rarely Seen in Public</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once a familiar figure who often accompanied Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> in his travels, Empress <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON> in recent years has been confined to a wheelchair and seldom makes public appearances. The 85-year-old empress married <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, who died Saturday, nearly 65 years ago and would have celebrated her anniversary later this month. Born March 6, 1903, <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON> was the daughter of Imperial Prince <PERSON> Kuniyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuni </PERSON>. She was brought up in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, attending the elite Peer's School for Girls. She later received instruction from two <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quakers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> and <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoads </PERSON>, who were credited with inspiring many of the democratic changes which permeated the private life of the imperial family. Mrs. <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> also tutored Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> to his fluent English. At age 15, Princess <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON> was one of several prospective brides selected for <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, then crown prince. He chose her over the objections of some powerful court officials, including the <PERSON> Fujiwara </PERSON> family that traditionally supplied imperial brides. They tried to stop the engagement by producing medical records of color blindness in her mother's family, but doctors disputed the claims and <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> made it clear he already had decided. Once betrothed, the couple met only nine times during their six-year engagement. The wedding, set for 1923, was postponed after the Great Kanto Earthquake in September left much of the capital burned and in ruins. They were wed in an elaborate ceremony on Jan. 26, 1924. On Christmas Day in 1926, <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON> became empress of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> succeeded to the legendary Chryanthemum Throne on the death of his father, the <ORGANIZATION> Taisho </ORGANIZATION> emperor. Married longer than any imperial couple in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s history, she called him `` okami,'' or honorable master, and he affectionately referred to her as `` Naga-miya,'' Naga from her name and miya meaning princess. She gave birth to seven children. The first four were all girls, and court officials urged <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> to take a concubine to ensure there would be a male heir to the throne. But the emperor refused, and the next child was a boy, Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, who was born on Dec. 23, 1933. <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitachi </PERSON> was born in 1935 and a fifth daughter in 1939. Two of their children died, a daughter during infancy and the eldest child, the former Princess <PERSON> Teru </PERSON>, at age 35 in 1961. The empress enjoys writing 31-syllable poems called `` waka,'' and plays the piano, violin and koto, a 13-stringed Japanese instrument. She studied painting under two of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s most respected artists, signing her work `` Toen,'' or Peach Garden. Collections of her works have been published in two volumes, and an exhibition of her drawings was held when she and <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1975. According to custom, she spent most of her time with her husband and family at the moated imperial palace in central <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> or their mountain and seaside villas. She kept busy with various indoor duties, including newspaper clipping for the emperor and keeping track of greetings to foreign dignitaries, imperial household officials say. Confined by a back ailment and hip problems to a wheelchair, the empress in recent years has rarely appeared in public. But her smile, graceful wave and devotion to her husband have made her a familiar, grandmotherly figure to the Japanese.
