<HEAD>Appeal for Funds to Rebuild Ancient Ethiopian Monomuents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GONDAR, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a modest tent surrounded by crumbling palaces where Ethiopian emperors reigned for 250 years, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> official appealed for funds to rebuild the grandeur of this Marxist state's feudal past. `` These sites are part of our universal cultural heritage,'' <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> told Western ambassadors, international donors and representatives of other <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agencies Thursday. `` The history of this region is as imposing as the historical remains are impressive.'' The director-general of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION>, Scientific and Cultural Organization arrived in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital Wednesday to dramatize the need for $ 14.5 million for <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s 10-year program to restore palaces, monasteries, castles and other monuments that <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> has declared heritages of mankind Mayor immediately flew to <LOCATION> Gondar </LOCATION>, 285 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, a city graced by palaces and castles built by emperors who ruled between 1632 and 1868. Palaces such as <LOCATION> Gondar </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> are in need of restoration because they have been used continuously for two or more centuries. <PERSON> Ras </PERSON> <PERSON> Beit </PERSON> is an 18th century edifice used as offices of President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON>'s government. Some monuments were nearly destroyed in warfare between different dynasties and in resistance to foreign invasions. Others fell into disrepair because of neglect. In need of repair are the 11 fantastical churches hewn from rock in northern <LOCATION> Lalibella </LOCATION> town, monasteries around <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tana </LOCATION>, the source of the <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nile </ORGANIZATION>, and the granite-carved obelisks of <LOCATION> Axum </LOCATION> which once rose 13 storys high. Axum's tallest obelisk, an intricately carved stone column that once stretched up 100 feet, has fallen. The tallest still standing is more than 75 feet high, the height of a 10-story building. They were built when a a flourishing kingdom existed around 500 B.C. in <LOCATION> Axum </LOCATION>, 341 miles north of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> in wartorn <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> province. The king and his subjects embraced <ORGANIZATION> Coptic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christianity </ORGANIZATION> in 330 A.D. During the Middle Ages this kingdom gave way, through palace feuds and intrigues, to others in the south. However by 1636, <LOCATION> Gondar </LOCATION> had become the capital of centralized authority in the mountainous region, giving <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> a political entity long before European colonization. <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s monuments `` are treasures, a legacy of civilizations spanning more than 40 centuries. `` Anyone who sees the state into which the masterworks have fallen would shudder and move into action to preserve these and other jewels of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s past for the common enrichment of present and future generations,'' he said. He appealed to the international community to contribute money, equipment and services for the restoration. The 50-state Organization of African Unity announced from its <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> headquarters the first donation of $ 10,000 to help restore treasures of one of the continent's most ancient civilizations. Ethiopian Culture Minister <PERSON> Ghirma </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilma </PERSON> said his country's rich cultural history had attracted scholars from many parts of the world. Ethiopian artifacts and art are to be found in museums all over the world, he noted. <PERSON> Ghirma </PERSON> said the government, established after a 1974 coup ousted the late Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>, was keen to see the ancient monuments restored. <LOCATION> Gondar </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lalibella </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Axum </LOCATION> form the Ethiopian Tourist Orgnization's `` northern historic route.'' However, tourism there has been handicapped since the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Tigrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> took up arms against the government 14 years ago, demanding more autonomy for the province. <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> took issue with reporters who asked whether money spent on restoration of ancient monuments could not be better spent on people affected by natural calamities like the droughts and famines which intermittently afflict the East African nation. `` Guaranteeing opportunities to learn about and share our common heritage is also indispensable,'' he said.
