<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The physician who operated on former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> said the colon surgery should n't interfere with his serving as secretary of defense in President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s cabinet. `` Sen. Tower is in excellent health and he should expect a 100 percent recovery,'' Dr. <PERSON> R.D </PERSON> <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> said Friday. `` And I see no reason whatsoever why he ca n't pick up where he left off.'' <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> and other doctors removed a polyp and a one-foot section of Tower's colon during a three-hour operation Thursday. The polyp and section of colon appear to be benign, doctors said, although final reports from an analysis of the growth and tissue were not expected to be available until today. There is little chance of previously detected malignant cells resurfacing, <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> added. Tower, 63, appointed defense secretary-designate by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Dec. 16, was listed in good condition Friday night, hospital officials said. The former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senator is expected to remain hospitalized another seven or eight days, and <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> has recommended that he rest in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> another four or five days after being released. Doctors discovered the colon polyp Dec. 27 when physicians performed a colonoscopy and removed a cancerous rectal polyp they had discovered in November. `` All of the malignant cells from the rectal polyp have been removed and there is nothing but a high likelihood that a cure has been achieved. I think it would be the remotest possibility that he would have any additional trouble,'' <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dignan </PERSON> said the surgical procedure is standard for a broad-base polyp and similar to surgery performed on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Physicians also removed lymph nodes and a small portion of Tower's small intestine. Tower must return for regular examinations to insure that other polyps do not develop, but will not be expected to make any changes in his diet or take any prescription medicine. Tower, who retired in 1985 after 24 years in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, served as an arms negotiator for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and headed the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s Iran-Contra investigative panel.
