<HEAD>Washington, Libya In Verbal Dogfight Over Photos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Libya, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> engaged in a verbal dogfight in the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> over the authenticity of photos that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> says prove a Libyan MiG was armed when it was shot down by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jets. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy said Friday the photographs clearly show a <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> aircraft armed with missiles, not _ as he put it _ `` a bouquet of flowers.'' He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pilots acted in self-defense after using evasive air maneuvers five times to try to avoid the approaching jets. The Libyan envoy called the photographs `` fakes ... fabricated pictures ... directed in a Hollywood manner'' by actors and clever editors. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> says the planes were unarmed reconnaissance craft. The already bad relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> worsened in recent weeks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assertions that Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s government is ready to begin production of chemical weapons in a desert factory outside <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> says the plant is designed to make pharmaceuticals. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s U.N. Ambassador <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> dramatically exhibited two blurred photographs Friday that he said showed missiles under the wings and fuselage of one of the two Soviet-built MiG-23s shot down by two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> F-14 Tomcats on Wednesday over international waters of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say they believe the other plane was similarly armed. The photographs were passed around the council during the session, which <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> had sought in order to condemn the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The session adjourned until Monday morning. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its British ally are expected to veto the resolution of condemnation drafted by the 101-nation Non-Aligned Movement. About 25 speakers, mostly from Arab and non-aligned nations, have denounced the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session. No one has supported it, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies have not yet spoken. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> says the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government wants to provoke a Libyan retaliation so it can launch a full-scale attack. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes raided two <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> cities in 1986 to retaliate for purported Libyan support of terrorism in connection with the bombing of a West German disco frequented by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen. A spokesman for Libyan Information Minister <PERSON> Rajab </PERSON> <PERSON> Abou </PERSON> <PERSON> Dabbous </PERSON> said Friday that 14 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes _ not two _ attacked the Libyan craft. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says the photographs were taken from videotape of the encounter made by the pilot of one of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft. It says they show two views of a single aircraft armed with Aphid and Apex missiles. However, not everyone was convinced on Friday. Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON> told the council that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military action was `` absolutely unfounded.'' He said the photographs were blurred and added, `` It's immaterial whether the Libyan planes carried any missiles or were just pure reconnaissance planes. ... We can not recognize the right of a military plane of one country to shoot down a military aircraft of another country just because they both happen to be very close to each other in international airspace.'' `` I'm not going to get into a hassle over the quality of image,'' <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> retorted after <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> criticized his evidence. `` The important thing is that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft made five evasive maneuvers to turn away from the oncoming MiGs. `` If you are walking down a dark alley at night and you see a man who has a gun, and you cross the street and he crosses the street, you slow down and he slows down, you speed up and he speeds up, you've got to realize that he's not coming to present you with a bouquet of flowers,'' said <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes were on a routine mission and acted in self-defense. However, the Libyan envoy reminded the 15-member council that in July a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship shot down an Iranian commercial airliner in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> because crewmen mistakenly believed it to be an attacking warplane. All 290 people on the plane were killed. `` We are in the country of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>,'' he told reporters. `` It is very well edited, very well done _ and it is not true.''
