<SECOND>PM-INS-Central Americans,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge To Consider Restraining Order Against INS On Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has turned south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> into a detention camp with a ruling that prevents Central American immigrants from traveling to other areas to apply for asylum, a lawsuit contends. The lawsuit, filed Friday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, seeks to reverse Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> rules of Dec. 16 that made it impossible for most asylum-seekers to leave south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or work while waiting 30 days for approval or denial of their claims. `` In essence, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has been transformed into a de facto detention area and asylum applicants are trapped there,'' says the lawsuit, which was filed on behalf of Central Americans and other asylum-seekers in the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> at the southern tip of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Before Dec. 16, asylum-seekers in <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> were allowed to travel to their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destinations to apply for asylum, often <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials said they adopted the new procedure in <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> to reduce huge case backlogs in those cities and to curb abuses of the system that delayed processing for legitimate asylum cases. At least 30,000 Central Americans passed through the area last year, according to <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> figures. Most of them enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> illegally in the <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> area of the Lower <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOC