<HEAD>New Emperor's Reign To Be Known As `Heisei'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s new imperial era was formally named `` Heisei'' _ or Achieving Peace _ to set a new tone for Emperor <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>'s reign after the turbulence of his father's 62-year epoch, the government announced today. Chief Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Keizo </PERSON> <PERSON> Obuchi </PERSON> announced the new name, which will be used on calendars and official documents. Under a 1979 law, and a custom dating back 1,300 years, a new name is assigned when a new emperor ascends <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 2,600-year-old Chrysanthemum Throne. Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> died today of intestinal cancer after a 3 -LCB- - month illness He was 87. His oldest son, <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, 55, immediately succeeded him. `` Heisei'' was chosen for <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>'s reign because the word, consisting of two Chinese characters, `` includes the meaning of achieving peace domestically, internationally and in heaven,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said in a statement. `` I think it is the most appropriate era name to reflect the coming ` new age,''' <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said. The new era officially begins Sunday, with this year becoming <ORGANIZATION> Heisei </ORGANIZATION> 1. The name was approved by <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s Cabinet today, and <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> signed with a calligraphy brush to give the measure formal effect. Reflecting <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s postwar democratic constitution, private citizens were included for the first time on the council that recommended three names for the new era to the Cabinet. The group also included <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers, <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officials and scholars. The opinion of the new emperor was not given much weight. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s reign, which began Dec. 25, 1926, was known as <PERSON> Showa </PERSON>, the era of `` enlightened peace.'' By the Japanese calendar, this year was Showa 64. During the <LOCATION> Showa </LOCATION> era, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> saw his nation plunge into World War II and suffer history's first atomic attack, announced its surrender, and later saw it rise to economic superpower status. On the death of <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s longest-reigning monarch, <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> succeeded automatically to the throne, becoming the 125th emperor in the world's oldest imperial line _ held by the same family since at least the 8th century and by legend since 660 B.C. In a ceremony a few hours after <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> died, <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> received three sacred treasures _ a sword, jewels and the imperial seal _ that have been handed down through the centuries. Other ceremonies were expected to extend over at least two years, ending with the formal enthronement. A debate over naming the eras of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s emperors had flared between opposition parties and the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which revived the era-naming clause in 1979 after it was dropped from the postwar constitution. The <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> favor the exclusive use of the Western calendar and charge that naming eras violates the constitutional provision that sovereignty rests with the Japanese people. The era-naming tradition was imported from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and reflected a belief that the sovereign controlled time itself.
</TEXT>
