 Most of the 94 Haitians intercepted by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> on a 30-foot wooden sailboat off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> have been detained until a judge decides whether they should be deported, authorities said. The Haitians, who told officials they had spent 15 days on the boat, were rescued Friday after it ran onto rocks off the coast of Grassy Key near Marathon, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said. `` This is the largest number of Haitians to get here in nine years,'' said <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, district director of the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Three of the refugees were treated at Fishermen's Hospital in Marathon. One woman had gone into labor, one man had suffered a possible heart attack and another man had fainted, <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> said there were ten pregnant women and three children in the group.
