<FIRST>r w PM-Hirohito-EndingTheWar     01-07 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Ending The War,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Emperor's Tilt to Surrender Documented</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> played a major role in ending World War II between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to documents in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> archives. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> paid tribute to the actions of <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> in helping to end the the hostilities and leading the Japanese people through reconstruction after the mikado died on Friday. The Japanese account of <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s role in the last days of the war was first made public when the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 issued the 1945 volume in its continuing series of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic documents. Historians regard his acts then as one factor influencing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision against including the emperor among Japanese leaders prosecuted for war crimes. One lengthy report to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> describes the <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> as changing his customary practice of acquiescing in all decisions of others to put the brakes on a futile war effort that was out of control. After the collapse of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> it was obvious to Japanese leaders that the war was lost but `` the force of militarism and the momentum which was carrying the war along were like a bicycle rolling down hill without brakes: there was no way to stop it and the army itself did not know how to give up,'' said the November, 1945, account of the Japanese version of events leading to surrender. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, a political adviser to Gen. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> MacArthur </PERSON>, the supreme allied commander, wrote the report quoting a long conversation with <PERSON> Hisatsune </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakomizu </PERSON>, who was chief cabinet secretary under <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s last wartime Prime Minister, <PERSON> Kantoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, an admiral, had been <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s aide-de-camp for six years and had a personal friendship with the emperor, unlike the earlier Prime Minister, Gen. <PERSON> Hideki </PERSON> <PERSON> Tojo </PERSON>, who was later convicted of war crimes and hanged. Thus <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> for the first time `` was able to express his true feelings through the prime minister,'' <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Sakomizu </PERSON> as saying. On August 9, the day <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> was bombed in history's second atomic attack, <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> decided that nuclear weapons and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s entry into the war provided needed justification for ending the conflict. `` The emperor agreed that the war should be brought to an end on the basis of the -LRB- allied -RRB- <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION> declaration,'' the account said. It continued: Six top leaders discussed accepting <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION> and deadlocked. Prime Minister <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, the navy and foreign ministers favored acceptance provided only that the emperor was retained. The war minister and the army and navy chiefs of staffs insisted on two other conditions -- that allied forces not occupy <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> be allowed to bring home its forces without surrendering them abroad. Unable to get the customary consensus, <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> went to the emperor, who called an <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> at 11 p.m. Deadlock continued, with the prime minister supported 4-3. `` Always before it had been the custom for a conference to reach a decision without directly involving the emperor,'' but because of the close division <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> asked him to decide, said the report. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sakomizu </PERSON> quoted the mikado as speaking out for peace and giving his reasons: `` 1. From the very start of the war, the plans and information of the military had been far removed from the facts of the true situation; `` 2. That to continue the war would mean the destruction of the Japanese people and the country and would also be disastrous to world civilization. and ... `` 3. Termination of the war in this manner at this time was in accordance with the will of God and the destiny of the world.'' Early Aug. 10, the imperial government messaged acceptance of <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION> with the understanding that the emperor would be retained. A reply three days later said the ultimate form of government would depend on the freely expressed will of the Japanese people. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> favored immediate final acceptance but most of the military again `` unalterabily opposed.'' <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> on his own initiative called another <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> for Aug. 14 at which he asked all to accept his decision to issue an imperial rescript ending the war. It was readied at 11 p.m. and the emperor decided on his historic broadcast directly to the people. <PERSON> Sakomizu </PERSON> also gave details of already-known unsuccessful moves by diehard army officers to prevent the broadcast by sealing off the palace during the night of August 15, attacking the prime minister's official residence and burning the homes of <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiranuma </PERSON>, the privy council president who had favored peace On August 16 the stunned populace for the first time heard <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s voice declare that the war `` has developed not necessarily to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s advantage,'' and was over.
