<HEAD>Japan Plans 29 Funeral Rites For Hirohito</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will bury Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> after weeks of ceremonies that will follow closely the rituals and pageantry of his father's funeral 62 years ago. The formal state funeral is planned for Feb. 24, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> news service reported, quoting government sources. There was no immediate government announcement. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> died today from intestinal cancer. He was 87. Ceremonies to purify the mausoleum where <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s body will lay, to enshrine his spirit and to mark the departure of the imperial hearse from the palace for the burial site are among 29 funeral rites planned. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> will head a committee to decide funeral details. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s father, <ORGANIZATION> Emperor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taisho </ORGANIZATION>, was buried 45 days after his death on Dec. 25, 1926, in an elaborate garden ceremony that included a funeral march of 6,000 people. `` Although there have been many changes since then, including major changes in the constitution, in practical terms there wo n't be many alterations in the funeral rites,'' a palace official said before <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s death. That would mean there could be more than 61 different ceremonies, rites and imperial court appearances extending over at least two years before his son <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>'s formal ascension to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 2,600-year-old Chrysanthemum Throne Many are directly linked to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s native Shinto religion, for which the emperor serves as chief priest. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> was considered a living Shinto god until allied occupation authorities forced him to renounce his divinity after World War II. The postwar constitution makes the emperor the `` symbol of state.'' Officials say <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s body will be placed in a casket two or three days after his death. The funeral, on a day that will be declared a national holiday, will include a procession of top officials and foreign dignitaries to a royal burial ground. In a departure from common Japanese practice, palace officials said the emperor will not be cremated. Government officials avoided talking about the funeral before <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s death, believing it inappropriate while he was still battling his illness. The 45-day period after <ORGANIZATION> Taisho </ORGANIZATION>'s death was likely related to the time required for foreign dignitaries to travel to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, since only boat transportation was available at the time, the palace official said.
