<HEAD>Japanese-Americans Mourn Death of An Emperor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where one-quarter of the population is of <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> descent, Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> was remembered as a symbol of unity who helped <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> emerge as a leading democracy in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, who reigned for 62 years, died today of intestinal cancer at age 87. His eldest son, Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, 55, immediately became the 125th occupant of the Chrysanthemum Throne. Elsewhere Friday, Americans made books of condolence in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> as officials planned to mark his passing in ceremonies during the coming days. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> offered condolences and lauded <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> for playing `` a truly heroic role'' in urging his country to surrender after the atomic bombing of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the close of World War II. Mourning was most evident at the Japanese consulate in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> had planted a tree during a 1975 visit to the Islands. The Japanese flag flew at half-staff and officials monitored Japanese radio accounts of <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s death. Consul General <PERSON> Tadayuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Nonoyama </PERSON> invited mourners to the consulate on Monday and Tuesday to sign a book of condolences for the royal family. <PERSON> Nonoyama </PERSON> said his own loss was made greater because he had known <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, once serving as an interpreter in the royal household. `` I have a deep affection for the emperor. He was a very sincere man,'' <PERSON> Nonoyama </PERSON> said. Sen. Spark <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, said he had great respect for <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, with whom he met on several occasions. `` The emperor's role as a symbol of unity contributed to the miracle performed by the Japanese people in developing their country as the leading democratic nation in post-war <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, politically, economically and culturally,'' <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> `` will long be remembered as the god who became a man, and through his personal humility brought respect and dignity out of the tragedy of war.'' In <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, plans to mark <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s passing would be formalized next week, said <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the State of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>'s Japanese consulate also would have a book of condolences for signing, she said. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, Japanese-Americans voiced restrained sympathy over the monarch's passing. `` I suspect that in a way the Japanese-Americans who are living in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> may take the death a little more seriously, or hard,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Duus </PERSON>, professor of modern Japanese history at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` When the older generation left <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> the emperor was almost like a Russian Czar, surrounded by religious awe. And the younger generation here, as a result, have a wonderful time-capsule picture of the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> their parents knew,'' <PERSON> Duus </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimura </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> chapter, said, `` This is a shock even though we knew he was sick. `` Even though we are Japanese-Americans there is still some strong feelings for our homeland,'' <PERSON> Kimura </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, Japanese residents planned a ceremony Monday to memorialize the emperor, but the state's <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> community planned no commemoration to avoid misunderstanding over <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s wartime role. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozaki </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION>, said the organization made arrangements for a `` kicho,'' or memorial ceremony for the state's 7,000 Japanese to bow before a portrait of the emperor and sign a condolence book on Monday at <LOCATION> Sakura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, a Japanese commercial area in downtown <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>.
