<HEAD>Fingerprint On Salad Dressing Jar Convicts 320-Pound Burglar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 320-pound man whose appetite got the best of him while he was burglarizing a home fixed himself a meal _ and one to go _ but was caught when authorities found his fingerprint on a salad-dressing jar. `` This man is no overweight Goldilocks sampling their porridge ... He's a brazen thief,'' Deputy <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Givando-Cline </PERSON> said Friday at the trial of <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. White. `` We have a man apparently overcome by the vigor of his own appetite who stops during the course of his own burglary and prepares himself a feast,'' <PERSON> Givando-Cline </PERSON> said. White, 24, of <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>, was convicted of burglary, fined $ 1,000 and sentenced to 5 -LCB- years in prison. <PERSON> Givando-Cline </PERSON> said <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who is 6-foot-2, entered a townhouse through an unlocked door on the night of June 4, 1986, while the family of four slept upstairs. The prosecutor said <PERSON> White </PERSON> took a videocassette recorder, tapes and $ 69. But White did n't leave after getting the loot, opting instead to plunder the pantry, <PERSON> Givando-Cline </PERSON> said. Littering the counters were a plate that previously held four salmon cutlets, an open loaf of bread, orange peels and pitchers of milk, water and Kool-Aid. The burglar also packed a snack to go of luncheon meats, cheese, oranges, ice cream and Kool-Aid, the prosecutor said. <PERSON> Givando-Cline </PERSON> said <PERSON> White </PERSON>'s fingerprint was found on a jar of Miracle Whip Light salad dressing in the kitchen. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <PERSON> White </PERSON>'s court-appointed attorney, argued that fingerprint evidence is not steadfast. `` For 20 years fingerprints can stay there,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` Think about that the next time you're in a grocery store and touch a jar of mayonnaise there.''
