<HEAD>Tremor Jolts Swiss Alps, No Major Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pre-dawn earthquake jolted the Swiss Alps today, but no major damage was reported, authorities said. <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>'s strongest tremor in five years, which measured 3.8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, was felt mainly in the region around the <LOCATION> Valais </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION> ski resort of <LOCATION> Crans-Montana </LOCATION>, the Swiss <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> reported. Tremors were felt up to 30 miles from the quake's epicenter, said the institute's chief earthquake specialist <PERSON> Dieter-Mayer </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON>. He said one resident called authorities to report a crack in a house wall. The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10 times greater. An earthquake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans, while a quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage in populated areas. A tremor of magnitude 7 is considered a major earthquake, capable of widespread, heavy damage in populated areas.
