<HEAD>Azerbaijani Refugee Count Reaches 160,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of Azerbaijanis who fled neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to their homeland in the face of ethnic unrest and a devastating earthquake has swelled to 160,000, an <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> official said today. Thousands of the refugees are camping in schools, clubs and other public buildings as they await resettlement, said <ORGANIZATION> Azerbaijan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bagirov </PERSON>, who did not give his first name. Others have been placed in new jobs and housing all over the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, he said, although officials are still trying to persuade both Azerbaijani and Armenian refugees to return home. The refugee situation in neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> is much worse, since the 90,000 Armenians who fled <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> have been joined by half a million left homeless by the devastating Dec. 7 earthquake. Previous figures refugees, issued in November, said about 75,000 Armenians and 75,000 Azerbaijanis had fled to their homelands. Ethnic violence between the Moslem Azerbaijanis and the Christian Armenians has torn the two southern Soviet republics for the past year, and the latest outbreak starting in November killed 43 people, according to today's Pravda. <PERSON> Bagirov </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> capital, was calm. The atmosphere in the city was described as `` explosive'' during ethnic unrest just before the quake. However, chief investigator Gen. Lt. V.K. <PERSON> Pankin </PERSON> of the national <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> told Pravda today, `` The situation is still complicated.'' His department has sent staffers from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to assist <LOCATION