<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stores covered display windows with white cloth, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION> turned its music down and the stock market closed today in a show of commercial restraint as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> mourned the death of Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>. And in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, an 87-year-old man hanged himself today, leaving a note that said in part, `` I want to follow the emperor in death.'' But while shock and a flurry of cancellations followed the sudden worsening of <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s health in September, his long illness had given Japanese time to prepare for the end of his 62-year era. The government declared an official six-day mourning period, and the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> called on schools and athletic organizations `` to unite together to suitably mourn the emperor.'' Thousands of people lined up at the Imperial Palace to pray and sign their names on registries to express condolences for <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, who died today of intestinal cancer. `` Of course it's a shock. I had hoped that the emperor would live as long as possible,'' said <PERSON> Masakichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Koizumi </PERSON>, 69, one of those in line. `` But it was inevitable.'' In downtown <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, a group of about 90 people marched for about an hour protesting the imperial system of rule. Television newscasters changed into dark clothing to express mourning. Although stock exchanges canceled their regular half-day sessions, banks, department stores and chain stores remained open. <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION> was open, but played its music at half the normal volume. Most stores in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s normally garish <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> shopping district turned off their electric signs and erected Japanese rising-sun flags topped with black streamers. At a <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> restaurant, clerks with black ribbons pinned to their lapels scurried to serve customers. Department stores covered their elaborate show windows with white sheets. `` We thought it would be better, given the circumstances, to cover up the decorative displays,'' said <PERSON> Haruhisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Hattori </PERSON>, director of advertising at <ORGANIZATION> Wako </ORGANIZATION> department store. But not everyone supported the expressions of `` jishuku,'' or self-restraint. `` I think it's crazy to do things like that for someone who shared responsibility for World War II,'' said a 33-year-old office worker, pointing to the covered Wako window. `` I had hoped the emperor would apologize -LRB- for the war -RRB- before he died.'' Questions over <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s wartime role _ whether he was an active participant in planning the hostilities, or merely used by militarists _ remain controversial in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, although most people express affection for the dead monarch and say they favor the emperor system. The anti-imperial protest went on for about an hour in downtown <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` I could not stand the thought that people outside <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are going to think all Japanese are emperor lovers and everyone is crying over his death,'' said organizer <PERSON> Ryuichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Harada </PERSON>. Passers-by looked uncomfortably at the marchers. `` I do n't believe it,'' one said `` Are they really Japanese?'' All major political parties expressed sorrow over the emperor's death, with the exception of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which officially opposes the imperial system <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition group, said the emperor's reign `` was full of bitter experiences and shocks,'' and pledged her party would work to use the lessons of history to achieve a permanent peace. `` The sad news of the passing of his late majesty the emperor has left me grief-stricken,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said. `` Our sincere prayers for his recovery were in vain, and I am at a loss for words.'' <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s fifth daughter, <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimazu </PERSON>, said her father had `` battled gallantly'' against his cancer. `` I hope he now will be able to rest peacefully,'' she said. `` He was n't a god, but he was somehow different from ordinary people,'' said <PERSON> Hiroko </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON>, 22. `` I do n't think I've changed inside because of his death, but I have a feeling an era has changed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.''
