<HEAD>Clamor Rising for Overhaul of Campaign Finance System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From lawmakers on Capitol Hill to their reform-minded critics and even well heeled lobbyists, a growing chorus of influential voices is calling for an overhaul of the nation's campaign finance system. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, has campaign finance reform near the top of his agenda for the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as does Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, the Republican leader. And change is being urged by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., whose <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> forces used a stubborn filibuster to kill a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> election-money package in the last <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats have no formal agenda yet, but their new majority leader, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, favors change, and the leader of the reform forces, Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., is ready to renew his fight in 1989 There is optimism at Common Cause, the self-described citizens' lobby, which wants to substitute public financing for individual and special interest money in the quarter-billion-dollar plus business of winning seats in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` It's going all the way to the top,'' says <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wertheimer </PERSON>, Common Cause president. `` There's a different dynamic now. An awful lot of Republicans are upset with the present system and talking about need for change. There's an unusual opportunity for 1989.'' Joining in the push are some people <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cause </ORGANIZATION> wants to send to the election sidelines, for example <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Baer </PERSON>, a senior partner-lobbyist in <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s big league law firms. `` Things have gotten out of hand,'' says <PERSON> Baer </PERSON>, who heads the 150-member Lobbyists and Lawyers for Campaign Finance Reform. <PERSON> Baer </PERSON> says there is deep and growing dissatisfaction over the seemingly endless congressional fundraising events _ sometimes as many as 10 in one night _ at which lobbyists fete candidates with $ 2,000 contributions from political action committees operated by industry, labor and ideological groups. The final tabulations for the 1987-8 election cycle have n't been made by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> says that through last Sept. 30, PAC money continued to grow both in total dollars and in comparison to campaign contributions from individuals. For the period, PACs pumped $ 35.7 million into all <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> campaigns, up 1.7 percent over the corresponding 21 months of the 1985-6 cycle. They provided more than one-fifth of the $ 159.8 million given to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates. PACs provided one of every three dollars given to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> candidates, or about $ 73.7 million of the $ 214.4 million contributed. The PAC money was nearly 24 percent higher than in the first 21 months of the 1985-6 cycle. As in past years, incumbents fared better than their challengers in the scramble for PAC dollars. Senators got $ 5.17 for every $ 1 contributed to challengers. In the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> it was 10 to one in favor of incumbents. When the votes were counted, all but six of the 411 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members seeking reelection received another term. Under consideration are spending limits that would slow or halt the rapidly rising cost of campaigns. Provisions could be included involving phone-bank support that labor gives far more readily to Democrats. And lawmakers are puzzling over what to do about huge sums in little-controlled and unreported collected by the national parties. Republicans have opposed altering the system for more than a decade, thinking that they benefit more from the status quo. But Democrats are getting more PAC money. Their fund-raising among individuals is catching up with that of the the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> already has pulled even in the so-called `` soft money'' race to put the bite on corporations and people who can afford a $ 100,000 contribution not covered by <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> limits. And labor continues to favor Democrats. Although <PERSON> Wertheimer </PERSON> is optimistic about action in the 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, he sees `` a tough battle because individuals who benefit from the current system, incumbents, will be writing the new rules.'' Aides say <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders want to negotiate a bipartisan bill. But House Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., is warning that if necessary Democrats will use their majority to pass their own package The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is a different matter. If they keep their ranks together as they did in the last <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the 45 Republicans can again prevent a vote on campaign legislation they think favors Democrats. `` We can have a bipartisan campaign finance reform bill or we'll have no bill,'' says Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> spokesman on the `` We can stop it in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> or we can stop it in the White House.'' <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> says that `` there's no middle ground on spending limits.'' This puts him in direct conflict with Democrat <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, who last year cosponsored a package calling for voluntary spending limits for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> races. Even with this apparent basic difference, <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> says he sees some unspecified `` bargaining room'' with <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> and the Republicans.
