<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     01-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Blacks Killed in Natal Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three black men were killed in township violence in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> province, police said today, bringing the official death toll from fighting among black political factions this year to 12. One of the three men killed Friday died when police shot into a gang of men who were stoning a township home, police said. More than 1,000 people have died over the past 18 months in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> township fighting, chiefly between members of <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>, a Zulu political organization, and supporters of the banned <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> Despite national emergency laws and restrictions enforced since June 12, 1986, political unrest has continued at a reduced level, particularly attacks on black policemen and homes of government employees in black townships. But in the first week of 1989, political violence has been reported every day. The events include stabbings and shootings in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION>, mine explosions near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, gasoline bombings of townships houses throughout the country, stonings of houses and cars, and ambushes of policemen. However, the deaths and injuries and the numbers of incidents are much lower than during the height of the unrest from 1984-86. Currently, most incidents occur in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> are fighting for control of segregated black townships. The front supporters accuse police of siding with <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>, whom they regard as a collaborator because of his position as head of the <ORGANIZATION> KwaZulu </ORGANIZATION> homeland government. <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> accuses the front of supporting the bombing and sabotage campaign of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He disagrees with front policies supporting boycotts, sanctions and strikes to end the apartheid policy of legal race separation. During the violence Friday, police said a group of blacks fired at a another group, killing one man, in <LOCATION> Mpumalanga </LOCATION> township, where a house was damaged by a gasoline bomb. Police said they killed one black man and arrested four men when they opened fire with shotguns and pistols at a crowd of blacks who were stoning a house in <LOCATION> Haza </LOCATION> township. The body of a black man who had been stabbed to death was found at <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s Halt, police said, and another black man was shot and wounded by an unidentified assailant in <LOCATION> Imbali </LOCATION> township.
