<HEAD>Missouri Oil Spill Possibly Linked To Problem At Refinery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Impact, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officials said a pipeline rupture that sent 840,000 gallons of oil into the <LOCATION> Gasconade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> last month may have been caused by a malfunction at an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> refinery that temporarily increased pressure in the line. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Canino </PERSON> said Friday that pressure increased in the pipeline laid in 1948 while valves at a refinery in <LOCATION> Wood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION><LOCATION> , </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, 170 miles east of the spill site in central <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, were switching some crude oil from the <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> pipeline into another line operated by <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Canino </PERSON> said company officials have not determined what caused the malfunction The oil from the spill, one of the worst inland spills in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, made its way from the <LOCATION> Gasconade </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and from there to the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> said a federal inspector visited the spill site last week to determine if <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> violated any regulations in its operation of the 435-mile pipeline, which runs from <LOCATION> Cushing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, to <PERSON> Roxanna </PERSON>, Ill. The oil lost in the <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> spill is more than three times larger than the amount lost in all pipeline accidents in 1987, the last year for which figures are available, said the spokeswoman, <PERSON> Suzette </PERSON> <PERSON> Paes </PERSON>. The oil erupted from a 35-foot rupture in a buried pipeline near the <LOCATION> Gasconade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, about 140 miles west of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. Also Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> announced that it had recalled 1,500 of 2,000 bottlers and brewers laid off Tuesday when production shut down after tasters noticed an oily aroma to the water used for brewing the beer. Water samples taken Wednesday by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> turned up no traces of oil or related chemicals. In a statement, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinhubl </PERSON>, senior vice president of brewing, said the company `` would return gradually to full production and full employment.'' <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> water department officials have said that while the water from city taps might taste and smell oily for a few days, there was no danger. Extra steps were taken in treating water taken from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> as the oil spill moved past the city.
