<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> today called for direct negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to resolve a dispute over a <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> factory <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials claim was built to produce chemical weapons. The Libyan leader made the statement at <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>'s best hotel, where he arrived unexpectedly to speak to foreign reporters. It was his first public appearance since two <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> jets shot down two Libyan MiGs over the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on Wednesday. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must understand that her policy of surrounding us and using force against us will absolutely fail,'' <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> said, speaking softly in Arabic. `` They must negotiate with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> directly and they should sit at the negotiating table with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> without their weapons to achieve peace in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>,'' he said. He was ringed by bodyguards during his appearance in a hotel lobby lounge. `` I think the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will be able to do this because they will have learned their lessons of the previous administration. There have been enough lessons. They will have learned that force does not pay, especially with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> said. `` We will not respond to force, only to politeness and direct negotiations.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> brushed aside <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s call for direct negotiations. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, attending a chemical warfare conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, said, `` Communications is not the problem, the problem is Libyan policy.'' But the official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity, also