<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HATTIESBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A half-dozen students in an adult literacy project were hesitant at first, but now they're all published authors. The book of six stories, `` Fireside Memories,'' was mailed last week to 200 people who helped keep the <ORGANIZATION> Hattiesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> going during the past year. The 24-page book is partly a `` thank you'' to those who have given time and money to the literacy project, but it's also a way to get the students interested in writing, said Project Director <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON>. When <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON>, volunteer coordinator for the center, first proposed to students that they write stories for publication, the answer was `` No way,'' <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> said. Some of the adult students do n't want to let their friends and coworkers know they have trouble reading, <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> said. But eventually, six students agreed to put their ideas in print. Some wrote their stories alone, others dictated to a tutor. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who has been working with tutor <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> for two years, wrote poetically about colors of Christmas: `` With all of its beauty of red, gold and silver and the pure white snow which stands for God's pure love for us all.'' `` We talked about writing what Christmas meant to him,'' <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> said. `` He came in with it, and it was written. It was not all in complete sentences, but I did n't want to touch it; it was free verse. The only things I changed were some possible spellings.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STORRS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What would a legal document be without a few `` heretofores'' and `` forthwiths?'' It probably would be better written and easier to understand, says <PERSON> Minerva </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neiditz </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writing </ORGANIZATION>, who is running a contest to find the best legal brief written in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> in 1988 For the contest, 900 law firms and state agencies have been asked to submit their best appellate briefs filed in either state or federal court. The deadline is Jan. 15, and <PERSON> Neiditz </PERSON> is hoping to receive at least 100 entries. `` Lawyers have been my most difficult clients because they all assume they can write. They're extremely sensitive to anyone criticizing them,'' <PERSON> Nieditz </PERSON> said. `` There is a tremendous amount of extra verbiage and pomposity,'' she said. `` So, I thought it would be an exciting first project for the institute to create this competition for the best legal brief.'' Briefs will be screened initially by members of the <ORGANIZATION> UConn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. Then a panel of six judges will make the final selection. Some details of the contest are still to be worked out. For instance, <PERSON> Neiditz </PERSON> does n't know how many runners-up will be named, she does n't know when the winners will be announced, and she does n't know if cash prizes will be given, although she's hoping they will In the event of a tie, <PERSON> Neiditz </PERSON> will cast the deciding vote.
