<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> touted his forthcoming budget today as a `` responsible plan'' that will cut the deficit and assure <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s prosperity without raising taxes. `` I leave as I came _ dead set against any new taxes,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in the next-to-last radio address of his presidency. The five-minute talk was taped on Friday because the president entered <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for surgery today to correct a curvature of his left ring finger. The president's final spending plan is due out Monday, a $ 1.15 trillion budget that is said to propose the elimination of 82 government programs while protecting his two-term defense buildup. It covers the 1990 fiscal year, which begins next Oct. 1. But since President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is slated to take office on Jan. 20, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s document has been branded in some quarters as irrelevant. `` It's a responsible plan which cuts the deficit without touching Social Security, weakening defense, or reducing benfits to the needy,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asserted. `` And the best news is that this budget proves it can be done without raising your taxes.'' `` Raising taxes would be the surest way to kill the economic goose that lays the golden eggs,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The president argued that his plan will contain additional funds for air safety, fighting crime, housing the poor, the war on drugs, and the space program, as well as fighting Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome, or AIDS. The president also warned that his defense buildup must be maintained, saying, it is `` the price of peace and security for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` My fiscal year 1990 budget provides for the needy, does not raise taxes, and by controlling the growth in spending, reduces the deficit next year by nearly $ 70 billion,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` This budget is a realistic program which protects the working families of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, provides adequate support for those who depend on government and helps assure <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s prosperity for years to come,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The president also put in a plug for his decision this week to back the large pay raise for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, judges and top executive branch officials that has been recommended by a presidential commission. `` We must be willing to pay for excellence in government or risk a government run only by people of wealth or by those beholden to special interests,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said. The 50 percent pay raise will be come law automatically unless each house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rejects it by Feb. 8. The plan includes a ban on outside speaking fees and other certain income and will formally be sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s budget on Monday. Giving the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s radio speech was House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, who expressed hopes for `` a new era of cooperation and good feelings'' between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the White House. Speaking about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, `` we in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leadership are eager to help him attain his announced goal of wider access for all Americans to education, to child care, to affordable housing and to a cleaner environment.'' `` We in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hope that the next administration, together with us, will usher in a new era of cooperation and good feelings between the legislative and executive branches of government,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said.
