<HEAD>Reagan `In Good Spirits' After Undergoing Hand Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s doctors surgically corrected a curvature of his left ring finger on Saturday and he was described as being `` in good spirits'' after the 2 -LCB- - hour operation `` The president is comfortable and completed the operation with flying colors,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s doctor, Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, said in a statement released by the White House. The operation was designed to alleviate a rather common but deforming condition known as <PERSON> Dupuytren </PERSON>'s Contracture. It caused the president's finger to curve inward. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s arm will be in a sling and his hand bandaged for several days. He he will receive no special medication `` other than routine post-operative antibiotics and analgesics,'' the statement said. `` It is anticipated that the president will have full use of his finger,'' the statement added. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was `` alert and responsive'' throughout the surgery, which began at 8:24 a.m. EST and was `` sucessfully completed'' around 11 a.m. EST. `` His overall health is excellent,'' the physician said. `` He's in good spirits,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said following the surgery. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> returned to his hospital room shortly after the procedure and was visited by his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, the spokesman said. `` Today's procedure is not expected to interrupt the president's normal work schedule,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> chatted with the team of physicians throughout the procedure, talking about horses and his upcoming return to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> returns to his home state on Jan. 20 after president-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is inaugurated. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> reported that the president's doctors began administering local anesthesia shortly after 7:30 a.m. to numb his arm and hand. The procedure was conducted by a team of physicians at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s operation consisted of a `` partial palmer and digital fasciectomy. The disease extended from the wrist to the tip of the ring finger.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> explained that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s finger was cut from his palm to the tip of his finger and that the diseased tissue was removed in order to allow the finger to move freely. The affliction causes the progressive, and usually painless, contraction of the fingers and is due to a thickening of the tissue called fascia in the palm of the hand. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neviaser </PERSON>, chairman of the orthopedic surgery department and director of the hand surgery service at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Dupuytren </PERSON>'s Contraction is a fairly common problem in men of Irish or Scottish ancestry. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is a descendent of <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> immigrants. <PERSON> Neviaser </PERSON> said doctors do not know exactly what causes the affliction, which consists of `` a cellular activity that changes the fascia, causing formation of bands and nodules. The skin becomes thin over the fascia and the contraction of the fingers start.'' To relieve the contraction, <PERSON> Neviaser </PERSON> said surgeons make an incision over the area in the <LOCATION> palm </LOCATION> where a band of tissue has formed. The fascia is carefully separated from the skin and removed. The incision in the skin then is stitched back together. <PERSON> Neviaser </PERSON>, who is not involved in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s operation, said only the tissue directly involved with the finger contraction is removed. Although the procedure to remove the diseased tissue is considered minor surgery and patients usually do not remain overnight in the hospital, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was to stay at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> until Sunday as a precaution, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The first lady was expected to stay overnight at the White House but to go to the hospital to accompany her husband home. Upon entering the hospital just before noon, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> nodded `` yes'' when asked if she had spoken with the president by telephone, flashed a thumbs-up signal and said he was `` fine.'' The contracture was minimal when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office in 1981 but progressed enough during the past year to require surgical treatment. Untreated, the condition eventually may involve all four fingers but the thumb, leaving the hand in a clenched, claw-like position. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> did not expect any further surgery to be necessary. After several days, the spokesman said, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s splint will be removed and he will only be required to wear a hand bandage. He will wear a so-called `` dynamic'' splint for several months. It is a splint that allows the finger to flex so that the muscles can be strengthened, the spokesman said. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said the physicians involved, besides himself, included Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogumill </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a consultant at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION>; Col. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and Maj. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlik </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Hand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION>. The anesthesiologist was Lt. Col <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandy </PERSON>. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohr </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> medical unit and members of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> at <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> took part as consultants, <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said.
