<HEAD>New Year Brings Integration, Ending 36-Year-Old Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Black and white students are in the same public schools for the first time in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION>, after officials settled a 36-year-old integration lawsuit, the nation's oldest `` The biggest problem has been kids not finding their classrooms,'' said <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Mizell </PERSON>, one of two administrators sharing responsibility for the new consolidated high school, after classes began Friday. `` It's working smoother than anybody thought it would,'' agreed <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, the other co-supervisor. <PERSON> Mizell </PERSON> was principal at all-white <ORGANIZATION> Greensburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was principal at <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, a predominantly black school. Although <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION>'s high school students all are going to class in what used to be <LOCATION> Greensburg </LOCATION> High, it will be next fall before their classes are integrated, officials said. For this semester, they have the same classmates and teachers they had when the year began. Friday was the first day of class under an integration plan proposed by the school board and approved Dec. 22 by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> made his ruling settling the nation's oldest pending desegregation lawsuit after two days of hearings, during which white parents demonstration against consolidation and black parents demonstrated for it. `` There is no question the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has been operating in violation of the Constitution of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said in his ruling. `` The board now has come with its own proposal to consolidate all schools in the parish and this means desegregation will be accomplished. `` In some areas, these schools are not fit for a doghouse,'' the judge added. The suit was filed in 1952 by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, whose 14 children all attended black schools, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. That was even before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s landmark ruling in the case of <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> vs. the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, that ruled that segregated schools are inherently unequal. About 70 percent of the 2,040 children now in public school are black, although the parish population is about 51 percent black. <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> is northeast of <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, the state capital. The school board, saying it could no longer afford segregated schools, combined seven schools into three _ one for kindergarten through fourth-grade students, one for grades 5-8 and the high school. `` Most of the adjustments are at the elementary school,'' said <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spears </PERSON>, the parish's first black superintendent of schools and one of only three black superintendents among <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 64 parish -LRB- county -RRB- and two city school systems. The elementary level also was where most of the obvious problems were. Kindergarten and the first four grades were consolidated at what had been <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> _ a predominantly black school. Three other elementary schools were closed, two for blacks and one for whites. `` Why could n't they have waited? I went into two classrooms and neither have lights. They have wires all over,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON>, whose second - and fourth-grade sons had attended a closed white school Kindergarten teacher <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chadwick </PERSON>, who came from a closed school, said her new classroom had no heat, one of her two windows would n't open, there were no electrical outlets, painting was incomplete, clothes racks were n't up, floors had n't been cleaned and the play area was so full of cars that recess was canceled <PERSON> Spears </PERSON> said all of the parish's schools are substandard, but the four closed schools were the worst. `` I think today is excellent for a start, and I expect to see changes of attitudes in the next couple of days,'' the superintendent said. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Self </PERSON>, a senior who had attended predominately black St. Helena High, said there had n't been any conflicts. `` I play basketball and that'll work out once we get to know each other _ when we learn each other's moves,'' he said.
