<TEXT>
 Four fighters were killed and 12 civilians wounded in battles Saturday between rival Shiite Moslem militias in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s bomb-scarred commercial district and south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, a police spokesman said. An uneasy calm prevailed Saturday afternoon following the clashes between the pro-Syrian Amal, which means Hope, and Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. Three fighters were killed and eight people wounded in fierce <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> street battles, said the spokesman who can not be named under police rules. The two groups also dueled with howitzers and mortars 30 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, killing one combatant and wounding four people, he said. The new casualties brought the casualty toll to 33 killed and 92 wounded the Dec. 31 outbreak of the latest round of violence between the rival militias. Shell explosions accompanied by staccato bursts of machine-gun fire echoed across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> through the night as <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militiamen launched hit-and-run attacks on <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> positions near the western edge of the civil war Green Line that divides the capital into Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, according to the spokesman, responded by shelling Amal-controlled districts of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to `` ease the pressure on its fighters.'' Syrian troops armed with AK-47 assault rifles and rocket-propelled grenade launchers moved into the disputed area before dawn and enforced a cease-fire, the spokesman said. In south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Iklim </LOCATION> <LOCATION> al-Tiffah </LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, Amal gunners shelled <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighters with howitzers in the villages of <LOCATI