<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s radio address Saturday, given by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>: Good afternoon. This is <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. In 13 days, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will complete his eight years as our nation's chief executive. I know I speak for all Americans in wishing for Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the blessings of health and happiness, as much rest as he wants and as much work as he wants, and a full and productive life in his retirement. For President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, all of us wish success in his mighty endeavor _ the strength, the vision, courage and ability required in that most important office on Earth, and the finest blessings of God. Let us work as Americans to begin the new year in a cooperative spirit. In a nation where free men and women think for themselves, unanimity is never possible; it probably is n't even desirable. But when we let the larger things that unite us transcend the lesser concerns that divide us, our nation can achieve the basic unity essential in dealing with foreign countries. As a spokesman for the loyal opposition and leader of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, one who has often disagreed with the domestic priorities of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, I want to express thanks as an American to this administration for improving relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, for helping to abate the crisis in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, and for encouraging the growth and sustenance of political freedom in countries throughout the world. In most areas of our foreign policy, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration have worked together. The only exceptions were how to deal with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. During the new administration, I earnestly hope that we will be able to achieve true bipartisanship in every area of our foreign policy, and I pledge to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the unstinting cooperation of the congressional leadership in seeking that end. On the domestic front, our nation struggles to overcome three deficits: the budget deficit, the trade deficit, and the social deficit, caused by the growing difficulty for average Americans in trying to pay for such basic necessities as housing, higher education and health care. Now we can not expect to vanquish those evils entirely in this coming year. But if we have the will, we can make significant progress against all three deficits. Both of our political parties are publicly committed to doing so. By working together, we can help our new president fulfill his announced promise of a `` kinder, gentler'' <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. We in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leadership are eager to help him attain his announced goals of wider access for all Americans to education, to child care, to affordable housing, and to a cleaner environment. Working together, we can remove the scourge of drugs from our streets and from our schools. We have made significant progress in this bipartisan goal. Let us work together now for full funding to make our pledge a reality. Working together, we can pass a clean air bill this year. Let's make that one of our objectives. By working together, we can clean up the murky areas of campaign financing, broaden the base of small individual contributors and reduce the influence of special interests. This deserves our commitment, and I now invite a joint commitment. By working together, we can steadily reduce and eventually eliminate the annual budget deficits that threaten our economic future. Both Democrats and Republicans made contributions last year to landmark trade legislation. Let us not abandon that effort until <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> attains the objective of a revived industrial base. This is going to be a very busy and productive year in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. I am determined that as far as the speaker can influence the schedule, we're going to perform our work on time. As we did last year, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will pass all of our regular appropriations bills before the beginning of the August recess. Now we in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hope that the next administration, together with us, will usher in a new era of cooperation and good feelings between the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> and Executive branches of government. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> faces daunting challenges, but by working together, we can assure that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future will shine just as brightly as our past. Thank you for listening, and good afternoon.
