quipment,'' <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> said. `` In the golden age of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car design, we used thick steel with very generous curves. It did n't fit very well. `` We went to simpler dies and less handwork and thinner steel and that evolved into a boxier-looking car,'' he said. `` It's more sophisticated engineering, you have to have much more precise dies.'' Standing beside a maroon <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 200 at the show were <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Westland </LOCATION>. `` The first thing that strikes me about the car is the outside,'' <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> said. `` It's the silhouette,'' she added, `` I do n't like boxy cars.''
