<HEAD>Long Waits for City's First Pollution Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drivers trying to get their cars checked before an anti-smog crackdown begins say they have waited in line for hours and even days for the five-minute inspection. `` I've come four times so far,'' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> said heatedly as he got out of his battered white 1976 Rambler at one of the 32 governmen stations. `` Now I'm plain nervous.'' The government and environmentalists say <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s 3 million vehicles account for 80 percent of its pollution, which regularly exceeds maximum acceptable levels for ozone. Starting Monday, the city says cars visibly contaminating the air will be stopped. Fines equal to 20 days' minimum wage, or about $ 76, go into effect for violators Feb. 1, even if they have a sticker certifying their cars are smog-free. To obtain a sticker, a driver must pass muster at one of the inspection stations set up across the city. Inspections are free until Feb. 1. After that, they'll cost about $ 3.80 _ the equivalent of one day's mininum wage. <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> said Thursday he had waited from just after midnight until 4 p.m. and had yet to get his inspection. He said he came in at 4 a.m. another day and found too many already in line. At a larger station, drivers said they had been in line only 30 minutes, but longer waits seemed to be the rule. At a parking lot in the south part of the city, 160 cars were in line at 10 p.m. one night for the next day's scheduled 9 a.m. opening, already more than the station could handle in a day. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said he was given a March 4 appointment at the La Viga station in south-central <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I'd be in violation by then,'' he said. A few drivers said some stations were issuing stickers in exchange for bribes when cars failed the test. <PERSON> Adela </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said her car failed its first check, but the inspector tried to sell her a sticker for $ 17.50. She offered him $ 11, but he turned it down. Her car passed a later inspection. <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, waiting in line with his'78 Dodge, said a similar thing happened to a friend who's a chauffer and took some company cars to a station. `` According to them, they were n't properly tuned and they charged 20,000 pesos -LRB- $ 8.75 -RRB- for the sticker,'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said Newspaper reports said places in line were selling for up to 20,000 pesos. Responding to complaints, Mayor <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camacho </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> on Friday urged citizens to report incidents of corruption to city officials. Taking action against pollution is good, `` but I'd like to see one of those buses come in here,'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said, watching a yellow and brown city bus as it trailed a stream of black smoke from the pipe on its roof. The testing so far is required only of private vehicles, which account for 80 percent of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s vehicles. In 1987, private cars carried only 18 percnt of 25 million daily passenger trips, according to official figures. Subway, buses, trolleys, light trains and taxis provided the other transportation. At the parking lot where <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> was waiting, drivers had taken matters into their own hands. <PERSON> Vilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>, a young volunteer, wrote license numbers on a waiting list for the first available appointment time, eight days later. She told drivers to come two days ahead to confirm the date and the next day to pick up a number. The plan included leaving cars in line overnight to assure their position. A guard was being paid about 45 cents apiece to watch them, but some drivers said they were staying anyway. Heated arguments resulted when newcomers tried to jump the line. <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> complained there was one mobile unit instead of two and it did n't open on time. `` There's nothing of what they have promised,'' he said. `` The people are obeying all the orders. Why do n't they do their part?''
