<HEAD>Band Leader Xavier Cugat in Stable Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Band leader <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Cugat </PERSON> was responding favorably Saturday to treatment for a lung inflammation but remained in intensive care, a clinic spokeswoman said. The spokeswoman said the 89-year-old Spanish-born musician may be moved to a regular room in Quiron Clinic in the next few days if he continues to improve. His condition was stable Saturday, according to the spokeswoman, who declined to be identified. Friends rushed <PERSON> Cugat </PERSON> to the clinic Friday for treatment of `` severe lung inflammation and high blood pressure,'' said his physician, Dr. <PERSON> Jordi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rius </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cugat </PERSON> has suffered four heart attacks and a stroke since 1980. In 1987, he was twice treated for lung congestion. Born Jan. 1, 1900, in the northeastern Catalonian town of <LOCATION> Gerona </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cugat </PERSON> is credited with introducing tropical rhythms into American dance music. When he was 4, he and his family left for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, where he became a violinist. After limited success in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as a classical violinist, he began playing Latin American rhythmic music with several bands before organizing his own. <PERSON> Cugat </PERSON> became a star with his band in the 1930s playing Latin dance music in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and later at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In 1970 he turned over his band to <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> <PERSON> Puente </PERSON>, and a decade later returned to live in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>.
