<HEAD>Radioactive House Cleanup To Cost $9.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSDOWNE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cleanup of a radioactive house contaminated by a professor processing radium in the basement will cost $ 9.5 million and involve digging up neighbors' lawns and possibly garages, federal officials say. It is the second major price increase for the project, which is being financed by the federal Superfund cleanup program. In 1984, the cleanup cost was estimated at $ 2 million. Last August, as the cleanup began, officials estimated the cost at $ 7.5 million. `` A lot of the areas we are excavating turned out to be contaminated,'' <PERSON> Nanci </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday. `` In some areas we went down seven to nine feet'' before finding clean soil. Officials found that portions of the lawns of four surrounding homes were radioactive. Since August, contractors have been pulling apart the house and its lawn. The house was contaminated in the 1930s and 1940s by a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> professor. By November, contractors had torn down the entire house and shipped it to a special dump site in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. Only the lawn remained, but that has proven to be much more radioactive than previously thought, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said. Instead of the 1,000 tons of soil contractors expected to remove, they will cart off 2,200 tons to the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> dump, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Janosik </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> project manager, said he expects the cleanup to be completed by May or June. `` I've never seen the price of these things go down,'' he said.
