<HEAD>Author Clive Cussler, Volunteers Search for Buried Locomotive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with hunt unsuccessful on Saturday,
railroad car part found, search to end Sunday; picks up 4th graf, `A Kansas...'
SUBS grafs 12-14 pvs, `Backhoes are...Dirgo said.' with 4 to UPDATE with
backhoes digging three holes, details on railroad part; picks up 15th graf
pvs, `The town...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BENNETT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Best-selling author <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Cussler </PERSON> led 200 volunteers Saturday in a search for a locomotive believed buried in a dry creek bed during an 1878 flood, but the hunt's first day ended with no clues unturned. <PERSON> Cussler </PERSON> said he was not optimistic after workers found only a part from a railroad car, some tubing and what appeared to be part of an old farm wagon. `` If I had five guys with magnetometers and lined them up we'd find it,'' he said `` But -LRB- with 200 volunteers -RRB- it's too unwieldy. None of them have ever worked together before.'' The search was to be completed on Sunday. A <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> locomotive reportedly fell 30 feet from a railroad bridge, along with 19 of its 25 cars and a caboose, on the night of May 21, 1878, when an enormous flood struck the area 30 miles east of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Twelve of the cars and the locomotive were said to have been buried in the sand. The front brakeman, fireman and engineer all were killed. <PERSON> Cussler </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, has become somewhat of a guru to people who dream of discovering lost relics. Through his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the author of `` Raise the Titanic'' has located 54 sunken vessels, including a dirigible. But this is his first buried train. He said he learned about the train from articles several years ago. `` I put it away and filed it and I used it for a germ for my book, ` Night Probe,''' he said. `` I brought a psychic out once. He did n't spot the train but he found a target I had marked.'' Volunteers used shovels and hand-held metal detectors while several archeologists and flood experts used a land radar unit to search. Some volunteers, like <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotzinger </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Fedoruk </PERSON>, said they joined the search because they are fans of the writer. Two backhoes dug three large holes in the creekbed in areas targeted by metal detectors. But water filled the holes about 10 feet under the surface. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> of <PERSON> Darwin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, found the flat car part, which he described as a horseshoe-shaped piece of metal that held a gear. If the locomotive is found, it will belong to the landowner, <PERSON> Cussler </PERSON> said. Since most of the equipment has been donated, the cost of the search is less than $ 1,000, said agency spokesman <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Dirgo </PERSON>. The town of <LOCATION> Kiowa </LOCATION>, near where the tragedy occurred, was renamed <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> to honor two of the victims' widows, sisters whose maiden names were <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. Local newspapers reported that about two weeks after the accident, a man named <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> <PERSON> Londoner </PERSON> searched for the locomotive, using a magnetized crowbar. The Rocky Mountain News reported that the crowbar suddenly plunged violently into the sand, dragging Londoner with it `` to the astonishment of the spectators.'' Two hours later, Londoner reportedly emerged from the bog to announce that he had found the missing engine 8 feet under the ground and some distance downriver from the bridge. However, the newspaper story does n't say the locomotive was recovered. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION>, has said he thinks it unlikely that the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> would have left such a large, expensive locomotive in the sand. He said the railroad was in financial straits, and human labor was cheap at the time. The locomotive was said to be worth $ 18,000, by one account. However, 79-year-old <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, whose father was a 15-year-old railroad worker at the time of the flood, thinks the train is still there. `` My father said emphatically that nobody salvaged the locomotive,'' she said. <PERSON> Dirgo </PERSON> said the most recent organized search for the train was in May 1953 by a <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> professor. `` They only searched an area of 150 by 400 feet and did n't have the kind of equipment we have now,'' <PERSON> Dirgo </PERSON> said.
