<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:PolishFilmmaker Adv11   01-07 1014</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Polish Filmmaker, Adv 11,1039</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Jan 11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Short Films Go A Long Way for Polish Director</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON>, the director of `` A Short Film About Killing'' and `` A Short Film About Love,'' believes the human condition can be expressed by the ways people observe and ignore the Ten Commandments. The winner of the first European Film Prize, who sees human frailty in its purest form, has set out to do short films about all 10. But anyone expecting nicely packaged sermonettes in <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON>'s decalogue will find the effect quite startling `` A Short Film About Killing'' contains what he believes is the longest murder in film history, nearly eight minutes of brutality that he himself describes as too horrible even for a horror film. `` A Short Film About Love' speaks equally of loneliness and need, leaving the viewer scoffing at the superficiality of most relationships and rethinking the common assumption that true love brings happiness. Long one of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leading filmmakers, <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> has remained relatively little known in the West. But these `` sophisticated and strange tales'' _ to use the words of one Polish critic _ may cause that to change. Already they have brought him far more acclaim than he ever expected. `` Killing'' recently won the first European Film Award, a statuette called `` The Felix,' in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The prize, to be awarded annually in a different European city, is intended to be <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s answer to the Academy Awards. Last May, the film won the 1988 Jury Award at the <ORGANIZATION> Cannes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>. `` Love'' has been submitted as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s entry in the Oscar's best foreign film category <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON>, 47, an intense, ironic filmmaker whose past work has focused on people faced with ambiguous moral and political choices, has finished shooting the other eight films of his decalogue and is editing them for state-controlled Polish TV. `` It's not a religious inclination to make the Decalogue,'' he said in an interview, `` it's just a look at how difficult it is to live, how complicated life is. `` Moses came up with the Decalogue 6,000 years ago. Nobody has ever questioned it _ no ideology, no politics. -LRB- And yet -RRB- we violate it every day. That's interesting.'' Interesting enough for <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> to work harder than he ever has in his life, he said. Instead of his usual pace of one film every four years, he is making 10 in a space of three years. `` Americans are always saying that if there is something good, you should shoot it immediately. And they are right. That's how it happened with the Decalogue. ... I'm surprised no one ever thought of it earlier. The first commandment that he completed was the fifth, Thou Shalt Not Kill. It resulted in the starkly titled `` A Short Film About Killing.'' The screenplay, which <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> co-authored with a lawyer who is active in political causes, portrays the murder of a taxi driver by a young criminal and the youth's subsequent execution for the crime. The initial murder lasts seven minutes, 44 seconds. `` Film killing has its own form,'' <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> said. `` We know how one kills or gets killed in movies. Unfortunately, in real life, one has to work very hard to kill a man. It's hard work.'' The ruthless hollow-cheeked killer, played by <PERSON> Miroslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Baka </PERSON>, struggles for what seems an eternity to strangle and beat to death the much larger taxi driver and then drag him down a river bank. Strangely, by the end of the film _ which portrays <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s mean streets at their meanest _ the audience is able to see the killer as a victim too. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the film has given impetus to a drive to outlaw capital punishment, a goal which <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> readily endorses. The movie `` is against the death penalty because it is against killing, any form of killing. Because I think that relations between people have become too brutal.'' Abruptly shifting gears from killing to love, <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> made a haunting film about the crystalline love of an innocent 19-year-old for a worldly woman in her mid-30s whom he observes with the aid of a telescope from his room in an apartment block opposite hers. The film, which refers to the Sixth Commandment, ends with their positions reversed and the woman longingly watching for the boy through the window. Love fails to bring happiness, but afterwards they are `` wiser, better people,'' said <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON>. The critical acclaim for the films is a complete surprise, he said. `` Beginning the screenplays and beginning the production, we really did not have any idea they would go beyond <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> said. `` They are such small films ... very short, cheap films. It seemed to me they were unusually local, although obviously we were trying to give them a universal character.'' `` Killing,'' is being shown in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and it to be distributed throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He said it may eventually be sold to an American distributor for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. For Polish audiences watching the films, there is unflinching faithfulness to the realities of life here, from a cafe that is out of tea at midday to the windswept, barren apartment blocks where families are packed like so many sardines. However, <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> is not striving to portray life in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> but values that apply equally everywhere in the world. `` It's the same experience for an American, for a German, for a Frenchman, even for a Japanese. ... Everyone is afraid of death, no matter what party he belongs to.'' He said portraying such elemental, universal values was his main aim. `` Maybe I did not always succeed, but I was trying to make them in their purest forms.'' Although critical of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political system, <PERSON> Kieslowski </PERSON> has continued to work within the state-controlled film industry rather than go abroad or underground. But he now avoids political themes in his work. `` I stopped being interested in politics a long time ago,'' he said. `` I hope it's for good, because it set me free.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Jan. 11</NOTE>
