<HEAD>A Guarded But Hopeful Movie Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a rip-roaring 1988, the film industry anticipates _ with wary optimism _ a new season that will bring such surefire moneymakers as <PERSON> Indiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and the `` Star Trek'' gang, as well as the return of `` The Fly'' and those hilarious folks of `` Police Academy.'' If box-office hopes are somewhat guarded, that's because the movie menu is leaner than usual. Last year's 22-week writers' strike has finally been evidenced in fewer releases for the pre-summer season, traditionally a slow period. The fall stepup in production assures that the rest of the year will bring a plentiful supply. A cautious note is supplied by <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Variety </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. After noting that the 1988 domestic -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> -RRB- gross would amount to a record $ 4.4 billion, he added a historical note: Previous industry booms have lasted 30 to 42 months, followed by an average 18 months of recession. The current prosperity began in June 1986. Hence a downturn is due, according to business cycles. The most awaited film event of 1989 is <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Indiana <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and the Last Crusade,'' coming on May 24. The two previous adventures starring <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> rank among the top 10 moneymakers of all time. The new collaboration of <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> has the added allure of <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s father, Dr. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Paramount plans a one-two punch that might help restore its position as the top-grossing releasing company, the crown now held by <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Buena </PERSON> <PERSON> Vista </PERSON>. June will bring `` Star Trek V: The Final Frontier,'' directed by Captain <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> himself, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Buena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vista </ORGANIZATION> hopes to hold its position with a varied program. The dramatic `` Beaches,'' with <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Midler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> as longtime friends, goes into national release this month. On the lighter side are two crime-oriented comedies, `` Three Fugitives'' with <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolte </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON>; `` Bank Job'' with <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Blades </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>; plus a re-release of `` The Rescuers.'' Episodic films are rarely proved successful, but <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> is trying again with `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Stories,'' a trilogy with films by <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>. Comedies have dominated the year-end product, and they will be in big supply this year. They include: _ `` Major League,'' a story of baseball misfits with <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON>. _ `` Let It Ride,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> as a gambler trying to get rich against all odds. _ `` Cousins,'' <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Danson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossellini </PERSON> in an Americanized `` Cousin Cousine.'' _ `` The Experts,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Travolta </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ayre </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </P