<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 07-08,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 7-8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Caution Prevails In First Week Of Bond Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond traders rang in the new year the same way they rang out the old _ with worries about inflation, the dollar and the stubborn trade and federal budget deficits lingering like a bad hangover. `` I think it's going to be a difficult year for the financial markets,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International He and a number of other economists are predicting that interest rates will head higher in the first half of 1989 due to the overall strength of the economy, although some experts are slightly more optimistic about the near-term. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> may do a little snugging here and there, but no major moves are needed,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said. `` I think they tend to feel that interest rates are already high enough.'' Short-term rates, in particular, rose sharply in 1988, reflecting the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s desire beginning last March to tighten credit to prevent inflation from heating up. Longer-term rates remained fairly stable, though. That same trend continued into the first week of trading in 1989, causing a more pronounced inversion of the so-called yield curve, which illustrates the difference between short - and long rates and normally slopes upward `` We're seeing a flatter yield curve overall,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Held </ORGANIZATION>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. For instance, the yield on the three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill has risen 0.21 percentage points to 8.52 percent since the end of last year, while the yield on the 30-year bond moved up only 0.08 percentage points to 9.06 percent Part of the reason for the rise in short-term rates so far this year is that fact that the federal funds rate, the interest banks charge each other on overnight loans, has remained relatively high. Some analysts say the rise in the fed funds rate represents merely a carryover of yearend corporate demand for money, but others say the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> could do more to keep a healthy dose of reserves in the banking system. `` There are a lot of things the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> could have said and done ... and did n't,'' said Held. Still, interest rates and bond prices remained relatively stable in the first week of 1989 trading, mainly because of the dollar's surprising strength in foreign exchange <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Index </ORGANIZATION>, which measures the price of all outstanding Treasuries, rose marginally since the end of last year. `` This strength in the dollar is giving us some breathing room in the year,'' said <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> downing of two Libyan jets in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> this past week had helped push up the currency, since the dollar is often considered a safe haven amid international tension. The dollar still remains a major concern among bond traders this year, analysts say, since the market sentiment toward it remains fairly bearish. A weak currency makes dollar-denominated bonds less attractive to foreigners and often sparks higher inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities. Besides the lingering trade and budget deficits, which helped spark the 1987 stock market crash, bond traders this year remainly acutely worried about inflation as evidence points to a generally strong economy. `` You're not going to see inflation falling,'' said <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, who noted that the businesses are still using their plants and equipment to near capacity. One bit of positive news this past week, however, came from the December unemployment data. Although the jobless rate last month fell to 5.3 percent, dropping back to a 14-year low, many economists noted that average annual earnings remained unchanged for a third consecutive month and that the average factory work week declined. `` That is n't symptomatic of a booming economy,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
