<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Investors Remain Confident</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concerns about <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s intentions over the next six months remain evident in the oil futures market, but overall investors remain confident. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 13 cents to close at $ 17.55 a barrel Friday. The contract recovered on Thursday to post a gain of 34 cents after losing 28 cents on Wednesday. Analysts noted that although investors have appeared optimistic that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would stick to its new six-month production agreement prices for contracts between March and June showed only small gains of between 5 cents and 6 cents a barrel. `` Although there has been a steady growth in confidence, prices still favor the near-buy months,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, `` so confidence erodes as the months go out.'' The 13-member cartel agreed late last year to cut back production to 18.5 million barrels a day starting Jan. 1 from over 22 million barrels a day. A worldwide oversupply of oil has kept crude prices weak. Since the accord was announced, prices have risen from around the $ 13 level. Among refined products traded on the exchange Friday, domestic heating oil futures closed narrowly mixed. Analysts said cold weather has not affected heating oil prices significantly because of adequate supplies and forecasts of warmer weather. The February contract for home heating oil closed 0.13 cent higher at 53.60 cents a gallon after rising 0.82 cent in Thursday's session Other contract months ended the day mixed. Gasoline futures followed crude oil, with the February contract settling 0.32 cent higher at 47.72 cents a gallon. Other contract months also ended mixed.
</TEXT>
